Homework #6¶

Problem #1¶

Figure 10.1 in Trefethan and Bau illustrates a Householder reflection that reflects the vector xx about the space HH to obtain the reflected vector FxFx on the x-axis. From properties of vector addition, we might be tempted to write x+v=Fxx+v=Fx, where vv is the vector in the space orthogonal to HH. However, Algorithm 10.1 defines vv as v=Fx+xv=Fx+x. The source of the confusion may lie in the fact that a "reflection" is more naturally defined in terms of a light ray "reflecting" off of a shiny surface.

To see that we can derive the Household reflector more naturally, consider an incident ray vivi that hits a reflective surface and reflects back reflected ray vsvs. This reflected ray satisfies the expression

vs=Rvi(1)(1)vs=Rvi

where RR is a unitary Householder projection of the form I−2PI−2P for some orthogonal projection PP. The plot below illustates the these rays.

Problem¶

Derive the projector PP needed to compute the reflector R=I−2PR=I−2P for incident ray vv. Show that the geometry using the "reflected light" analogy is consistent with the vector addition properties we know and with Algorithm 10.1. Provide a sample incident ray and show that your reflection RR produces the expected reflected ray.

Hint: For this problem, you don't need to know anything about how light reflects, but should use the fact that the angles that the incident ray and reflected ray make with the surface normal are equal.

To derive the Household reflector RR more naturally, we consider an incident ray vivi that hits a reflective surface and reflects back reflected ray vrvr. This reflected ray satisfies the expression;

vr=Rvi                         (1)(2)(2)vr=Rvi                         (1)

From the diagram above, if vrvr is the reflected ray from the reflection of an incident ray vivi with respect to the surface normal nsns, then ∥vr∥=∥vi∥‖vr‖=‖vi‖ and PP is the projection of vivi onto the surface normal.

For this case, the surface normal is assumed to be a unit vector that is ∥ns∥=1‖ns‖=1.

Using the law of reflection i.e. θr=θi=θθr=θi=θ, thus u′=u′′=uu′=u″=u.

Also from the diagram above, we see that the incident and reflected rays are given by; vi=u+Pvi                         (2)vr=u−Pvi                         (3)(3)(4)(3)vi=u+Pvi                         (2)(4)vr=u−Pvi                         (3)

Making uu the subject in equation (1) and substituting in (2), we obtain; u=vi−Pvi⇒vr=vi−Pvi−Pvi=(I−2P)vi                         (4)(5)(6)(7)(5)u=vi−Pvi(6)⇒vr=vi−Pvi−Pvi(7)=(I−2P)vi                         (4)

Therefore comparing equations (1) and (4), we obtain that unitary Householder R=I−2PR=I−2P.

Since PP is the projection of vivi onto the surface normal, then from the diagram, P is given by;

P=cos(θ)ns(8)(8)P=cos⁡(θ)ns

But cos(θ)=ns⋅vicos⁡(θ)=ns⋅vi, therefore

P=(ns⋅vi)ns(9)(9)P=(ns⋅vi)ns

def plot_vec(v,color='k',scale = 1,dir=1,label=''):
    v0 = float(v[0])
    v1 = float(v[1])
    L = scale
    
    if dir == 1:
        o1,o2,e1,e2 = (0,0,v0,v1)
    else:
         o1,o2,e1,e2 = (v0,v1,-v0,-v1)
        
    arrow(o1,o2,e1,e2, 
          head_width=L*0.07, \
          head_length=L*0.1, \
          fc=color, \
          ec=color, \
          length_includes_head = True, \
          label=label)

    fstr = {'float' : "{:>10.4f}".format}
    with printoptions(formatter=fstr):

    print("")
In [19]:
def QR_House(A):
    m,n = A.shape

    R = A.copy()
    Q = eye(m)   # Update Q
    for j in range(n):
        x = R[j:m,j:j+1]
        I = eye(m-j)    
        s = 1 if x[0] >= 0 else -1     # sign function, with sign(0)  = 1
        v = s*linalg.norm(x,2)*I[:,0:1] + x
        v = v/linalg.norm(v,2)
        F = I - 2*(v@v.T)
        R[j:m,j:n] = F@R[j:m,j:n]
        Q[j:] = F @ Q[j:]
    return Q.T,R

Problem #3¶
Problem 6.5 (page 47) in TB asked you to show that for a non-zero projector PP, we have ∥P∥2≥1‖P‖2≥1, with equality if and only if PP is an orthogonal projector.  One solution to this problem is to use the SVD decomposition of the projector PP.


However, the SVD approach really doesn't provide much geometrical insight into the different between general projectors and orthogonal projectors.  For this problem, show that you can demonstrate the following using only a geometrical argument.


    

  • Show that for a non-zero projector, we have  ∥P∥2≥1‖P‖2≥1. 
    • 



Then show the two parts of the "if and only if".


    

  • (⟸)(⟸) Show that if PP is an orthogonal projector, we have ∥P∥2=1‖P‖2=1
    

    • 

  • (⟹)(⟹)Show that if ∥P∥2=1‖P‖2=1, PP must be orthogonal.
    

    • 



To demonstrate the above geometrically, start with a decomposition of a vector x∈Rmx∈Rm into unique components in subspaces S1=range(P)S1=range(P) and S2=range(I−P)S2=range(I−P) given by

x=Px+(I−P)x(10)(10)x=Px+(I−P)x
You can define angles between subspaces using this idea

(Px)T(I−P)x=∥Px∥2∥(I−P)x∥2cosθ(11)(11)(Px)T(I−P)x=‖Px‖2‖(I−P)x‖2cos⁡θ
where θθ is the angle between subspaces S1S1 and S2S2.  Then use the definition of the matrix 2-norm as

∥P∥2=maxx∥Px∥2∥x∥2(12)(12)‖P‖2=maxx‖Px‖2‖x‖2
and show that the maximum will be 1 if and only if θ=π/2θ=π/2.
